Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Nepal. The Nepali authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
The Government of Nepal has announced the suspension of all international flights from 2359 local time on 22 March, until 31 March. We are working with airlines and the authorities to try to find a solution. British Nationals who wish to travel to the UK to email BEKathmandu.Details@fco.gov.uk with their:
names
location
passport number
email address and
phone number
For information on how to return to the UK from Nepal, see Return to the UK
Travel restrictions
The Government of Nepal announced its intention to deny entry to Nepal to certain foreign nationals, including British nationals from 20 March–15 April. Until then, Nepal’s land-based entry crossings into Nepal are closed to foreigners from third countries. Entry is only permitted via Tribhuvan International Airport.
Nepal is not issuing tourist visas on arrival to any foreign nationals. Those entering on existing tourist visas must show a valid swab test PCR certificate completed no more than 7 days before their entry to Nepal. This requirement is being rigorously enforced. Those entering must subsequently stay in self-quarantine for 14 days upon arrival.
Local measures
The Government of Nepal will enforce movement restrictions across the country for one week from 06:00 on Tuesday 24 March. All outside movement, except for emergencies or to purchase essentials, will be prohibited. Anyone who defies this order could face a jail sentence and/or a fine.
The Nepali authorities have introduced number of measures to limit the spread of the virus, including the closure of some cultural and sporting facilities, and social gatherings above 25 people. You should comply fully with these. Testing and isolation for COVID-19 is limited to certain Government hospitals, where services are basic.
Permissions for mountaineering expeditions for Spring 2020 (including existing permissions) have been suspended.
You should check the Department of Immigration website for the latest information. Keep up to date with information from your tour operator, transport or accommodation provider on the impact on any existing travel plans.
Further information
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
You can find more information about cases in Nepal on the TravelHealthPro website.
